<tr>
    <td  bgcolor="#000080"><FONT color="#FFFFFF">&nbsp;Subject:&nbsp;RE: Ogres vs. Trolls</font></td>
</tr>
<tr>
    <td  bgcolor="#DCDCDC" valign="TOP"><table width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" border="0">
<tr>
    <td  bgcolor="#DCDCDC" width="100%" valign="top"><tt><font color="#000000">
Author:&nbsp;<a href="mailto:&#114;&#97;&#121;&#111;&#110;&#110;&#101;&#114;&#64;&#104;&#111;&#116;&#109;&#97;&#105;&#108;&#46;&#99;&#111;&#109;?subject=RE: Ogres vs. Trolls">Brugdurk</a>&nbsp;(mke-65-25-165-121.wi.rr.com)<br>
Date:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;11-07-2001 17:29<br><br>
I really cant devulge too much into playing a troll.....  Okay.  I cant go into playing a troll at all, since the only time I have is when Ive needed to have a look around Grobb for an item that a merchant might sell.  Playing an ogre has a high degree of difficulity.  First off, Im level 19, and I've been to a bank once.  There arent alot of areas around Oggok that you want to be playing in, in low levels, so once you migrate out, you seperate yourself from a bank, merchants, and friendly NPCs.  Secondly, due to the low intelligence and wisdom of these less than handsome guys (and gals), it can take forever to raise some skills.  With my main character, a high elf wizard, there was never a problem past 12th level maxing out my skills with a few minutes.  Spells seem to go by themselves, sense heading took a minute or two, etc...  At 19th level, I have only the combat skills maxed.  Offense, dodge, defense, dual wield, dual attack, kick, dodge....  and even these didnt max out right away.  It wasent until I dedicated an entire day of nothing but total hack and slash in Oasis, to raise these skills to where they were.  Last week I spend 35 points in 2hs, and I have yet to raise it.  <BR>
<BR>
     In conclusion, I would not make an Ogre a main character.  Its just not meant to be.  It requires lots of travel time, to get to a city that can stand the sight of you (and your smell), or countless hours of killing or questing to get a tolerable faction with a popular city, while usually lowering it in another at the same time.  A low charismia means high prices, which means spending more, which means having to kill more....  An ogre will make an awsome secondary character though.  After 30 levels of root, nuke, root, nuke, root, med, root, nuke, root, nuke, med, root, nuke, root, nuke, med, the opportunity to stand in the front line and wack anything that moved was very welcomed.  Supplies could be purchased through an alternate character, and there was no need to worry about faction or finding an NPC to sell to me.<BR>
<BR>
Brugdurk<BR>
-Innoruuk</font></tt></td>
</tr>
